once it got here,
it spread very quickly.

00:18:04.642 --> 00:18:06.851
♫ <i>How much goin' have you got</i>

00:18:06.894 --> 00:18:11.397
♫ <i>And I wonder</i>
<i>about your friends that are not</i>

00:18:11.524 --> 00:18:13.858
♫ <i>I wonder</i>

00:18:13.984 --> 00:18:15.485
♫ <i>I wonder</i>

00:18:19.406 --> 00:18:21.658
♫ <i>Wonder I do</i>

00:18:21.700 --> 00:18:25.078
<i>(Willem Möller)</i>
I remember I was in high school

00:18:26.038 --> 00:18:30.375
and we heard this song, ''I wonder
how many times you've had sex?''

00:18:30.417 --> 00:18:33.044
And at that time South Africa
was very conservative.

00:18:33.087 --> 00:18:35.421
It was the height of apartheid,

00:18:36.173 --> 00:18:38.383
and there wasn't television here.

00:18:38.425 --> 00:18:41.886
That's how conservative it was,
'cause television was communist.

00:18:41.929 --> 00:18:44.681
It was really... You wouldn't believe.

00:18:45.891 --> 00:18:47.725
Everything was restricted,
everything was censored.

00:18:47.852 --> 00:18:49.227
Everything was...

00:18:49.270 --> 00:18:51.437
And here's this guy singing this song.

00:18:51.564 --> 00:18:54.232
<i>''Who's that?'' Said, ''That's Rodriguez.''</i>

00:18:54.275 --> 00:18:58.570
<i>And he became something</i>
<i>of a rebel sort of icon.</i>

00:18:59.071 --> 00:19:01.781
<i>But the strange thing was</i>
<i>that we all bought his records.</i>

00:19:01.866 --> 00:19:04.742
Everybody I knew had his records.
<i>I Wonder,</i>

00:19:05.411 --> 00:19:07.036
that was the big song
that everybody was singing

00:19:07.079 --> 00:19:08.580
and we all bought a record.

00:19:08.622 --> 00:19:12.292
And there he was on the cover,
sort of a hippy with shades.

00:19:12.418 --> 00:19:15.545
But nobody knew anything about him.
He was a mystery.

00:19:15.588 --> 00:19:19.465
Unlike other artists
that you could read about from America,

00:19:19.592 --> 00:19:24.095
get to know something about them,
there was zilch. Nobody knew anything.

00:19:24.138 --> 00:19:28.433
It was a mystery. We only had
his picture on the cover of the record.

00:19:28.559 --> 00:19:29.934
<i>(</i>♫ <i>Jane S. Piddy</i> by Rodriguez)

00:19:30.060 --> 00:19:34.647
♫ <i>Now you sit there thinking</i>
<i>Feeling insecure</i>

00:19:34.773 --> 00:19:39.986
♫ <i>The mocking court jester</i>
<i>Claims there is no proven cure</i>

00:19:40.779 --> 00:19:45.825
♫ <i>Go back to your chamber</i>
<i>Your eyes upon the wall</i>

00:19:45.910 --> 00:19:51.664
♫ <i>Cos you got no one to listen</i>
<i>You got no one to call</i>

00:19:53.667 --> 00:19:55.793
♫ <i>And you think I'm curious</i>

00:19:55.836 --> 00:19:57.253
<i>(Segerman) The album</i>
<i>was exceptionally popular.</i>

00:19:57.296 --> 00:20:00.965
<i>To many of us South Africans,</i>
<i>he was the soundtrack to our lives.</i>

00:20:01.008 --> 00:20:03.760
<i>In the mid-'70s,</i>
<i>if you walked into a random</i>

00:20:03.802 --> 00:20:05.762
<i>white, liberal,</i>
<i>middle-class household</i>

00:20:05.804 --> 00:20:08.348
<i>that had a turntable</i>
<i>and a pile of pop records</i>

00:20:08.474 --> 00:20:11.100
<i>and if you flipped through the records</i>
<i>you would always see</i>

00:20:11.143 --> 00:20:12.810
Abbey Road <i>by The Beatles</i>.

00:20:12.937 --> 00:20:14.938
You would always see
<i>Bridge Over Troubled Water</i>

00:20:14.980 --> 00:20:16.481
by Simon and Garfunkel.

00:20:16.523 --> 00:20:19.150
And you would always see
<i>Cold Fact</i> by Rodriguez.

00:20:19.276 --> 00:20:22.320
To us, it was one of the most
famous records of all time.

00:20:23.030 --> 00:20:25.782
<i>The message it had was:</i>
<i>''Be anti-establishment.''</i>

00:20:25.824 --> 00:20:28.159
<i>One song's called</i>
Anti-Establishment Blues.

00:20:28.285 --> 00:20:29.953
We didn't know what the word
''anti-establishment'' was

00:20:29.995 --> 00:20:33.122
until it cropped up on a Rodriguez song
and then we found out,

00:20:33.165 --> 00:20:36.167
it's OK to protest against your society,

00:20:36.293 --> 00:20:39.087
to be angry with your society.

00:20:39.838 --> 00:20:42.340
Because we lived in a society

00:20:42.508 --> 00:20:45.927
where every means was used
to prevent apartheid from,

00:20:46.929 --> 00:20:49.013
you know, coming to an end,

00:20:50.349 --> 00:20:53.518
this album somehow had in it...

00:20:53.602 --> 00:20:59.607
lyrics that almost set us free
as oppressed peoples.

00:21:01.277 --> 00:21:03.361
Any revolution needs an anthem

00:21:03.404 --> 00:21:06.239
and in South Africa
<i>Cold Fact</i> was the album

00:21:06.365 --> 00:21:08.783
that gave people permission

00:21:08.867 --> 00:21:13.955
to free their minds
and to start thinking differently.

00:21:14.039 --> 00:21:15.540
<i>(</i>♫ <i> The Establishment Blues</i> by Rodriguez)

00:21:15.582 --> 00:21:18.251
♫ <i>The mayor hides the crime rate</i>
<i>Council woman hesitates</i>

00:21:18.377 --> 00:21:22.130
♫ <i>Public gets irate</i>
<i>But forgets the vote date</i>

00:21:22.214 --> 00:21:26.217
♫ <i>This system's gonna fall soon</i>
<i>To an angry young tune</i>

00:21:26.260 --> 00:21:28.761
♫ <i>And that's a concrete cold fact</i>

00:21:29.430 --> 00:21:32.390
<i>(Segerman) It may seem strange</i>
<i>that South African record companies</i>

00:21:32.558 --> 00:21:34.934
<i>didn't do more</i>
<i>to try and track down Rodriguez,</i>

00:21:34.977 --> 00:21:36.936
<i>but, actually,</i>
<i>if you look back at the time</i>

00:21:36.979 --> 00:21:39.939
<i>we were in the middle of apartheid,</i>
<i>the height of apartheid.</i>

00:21:39.982 --> 00:21:43.151
<i>South Africa was under sanctions</i>
<i>from countries from all over the world.</i>

00:21:43.235 --> 00:21:45.737
<i>South African musicians</i>
<i>were not allowed to play overseas.</i>

00:21:45.821 --> 00:21:48.906
<i>No foreign acts</i>
<i>were allowed to visit South Africa.</i>

00:21:48.949 --> 00:21:50.992
<i>It was a closed-door situation</i>

00:21:51.076 --> 00:21:53.161
<i>between South Africa</i>
<i>and the rest of the world.</i>

00:21:53.245 --> 00:21:57.165
♫ <i>Woke up this morning</i>
<i>with an ache in my head</i>

00:21:57.249 --> 00:22:01.085
♫ <i>I splashed on my clothes</i>
<i>as I spilled out of bed</i>

00:22:01.128 --> 00:22:05.256
♫ <i>I opened the window</i>
<i>to listen to the news</i>

00:22:05.299 --> 00:22:09.969
♫ <i>But all I heard</i>
<i>was the establishment's blues</i>

00:22:10.012 --> 00:22:12.263
<i>(Segerman) The countries around</i>
<i>the world were saying horrible things</i>

00:22:12.306 --> 00:22:13.765
<i>about the apartheid government</i>

00:22:13.849 --> 00:22:16.934
<i>but we didn't know</i>
<i>because they controlled the news.</i>

00:22:17.019 --> 00:22:20.271
<i>The majority of the population</i>
<i>had been marginalised</i>

00:22:20.314 --> 00:22:23.816
<i>and forced out of the commerce in areas.</i>

00:22:23.942 --> 00:22:25.693
<i>It was what had happened</i>
<i>in Nazi Germany.</i>

00:22:25.778 --> 00:22:27.653
<i>It was a spin-off from Nazi Germany,</i>

00:22:27.780 --> 00:22:30.698
<i>but if a newspaper published it,</i>
<i>they'd get prosecuted.</i>

00:22:30.783 --> 00:22:34.786
<i>So, because of that, South Africa had</i>
<i>achieved a pariah status in the world.</i>

00:22:34.828 --> 00:22:37.622
<i>There were cultural boycotts.</i>
<i>There were sporting boycotts.</i>

00:22:37.664 --> 00:22:41.125
<i>It was a very isolated society.</i>
<i>So we were cut off</i>.

00:22:41.210 --> 00:22:42.794
We all knew apartheid was wrong,

00:22:42.878 --> 00:22:44.045
but living in South Africa,

00:22:44.129 --> 00:22:45.463
there wasn't much, as a white person,

00:22:45.631 --> 00:22:46.798
you could do about it,

00:22:46.840 --> 00:22:48.633
'cause the government was very strict.

00:22:48.717 --> 00:22:50.802
It was a military state,
to a large degree.

00:22:50.886 --> 00:22:52.387
If you spoke out against apartheid,

00:22:52.471 --> 00:22:54.472
you could be thrown into prison
for three years.

00:22:54.515 --> 00:22:57.809
<i>So although a lot of whites</i>
<i>were part of the struggle,</i>

00:22:57.851 --> 00:22:59.519
<i>the majority of whites were not.</i>

00:22:59.645 --> 00:23:03.981
<i>You were watched. There were spies.</i>
<i>It was scary and people were scared.</i>

00:23:04.066 --> 00:23:06.901
But out of the Afrikaans
community emerged

00:23:06.985 --> 00:23:09.987
a group of Afrikaans
musicians, songwriters,

00:23:10.072 --> 00:23:14.325
and for them, when they heard Rodriguez,
it was like a voice spoke to them

00:23:14.410 --> 00:23:18.329
and said, ''Guys, there's a way out.
There's a way out.

00:23:18.372 --> 00:23:21.499
''You can write music.
You can write imagery.

00:23:21.667 --> 00:23:23.167
''You can sing, you can perform.''

00:23:23.252 --> 00:23:27.004
And that was where, really,
the first opposition to apartheid

00:23:27.089 --> 00:23:29.674
came from inside
the Afrikaans community.

00:23:29.758 --> 00:23:33.177
It was these young Afrikaans guys
and, to a man,

00:23:33.220 --> 00:23:35.763
they'll tell you
they were influenced by Rodriguez.

00:23:35.848 --> 00:23:38.015
<i>Koos Kombuis. Willem Möller.</i>

00:23:38.100 --> 00:23:39.892
<i>The late Johannes Kerkorrel.</i>

00:23:40.018 --> 00:23:45.523
The guys who were regarded as the icons
of the Afrikaans music revolution

00:23:45.691 --> 00:23:48.067
will all tell you,
''Rodriguez was our guy.''

00:23:48.193 --> 00:23:49.861
(speaking Afrikaans)

00:23:51.864 --> 00:23:53.739
<i>(Möller)</i>
<i>We call it the Voëlvry movement</i>

00:23:53.866 --> 00:23:56.367
<i>of Afrikaans artists</i>
<i>singing against apartheid.</i>

00:23:56.452 --> 00:23:59.245
All of us listened to Rodriguez
at some point. All of us.

00:23:59.371 --> 00:24:01.372
<i>It had an enormous impact.</i>

00:24:01.457 --> 00:24:03.958
<i>It made you just think</i>
<i>that there's another way.</i>

00:24:04.376 --> 00:24:08.254
What's presented to you
by the establishment isn't all theirs.

00:24:08.380 --> 00:24:10.047
(rock music playing)

00:24:10.090 --> 00:24:12.884
♫ <i>Set if off, set if off</i>
♫ <i>Set if off, set if off</i>

00:24:13.051 --> 00:24:16.804
♫ <i>Set if off, set if off</i>
♫ <i>Set if off, set if off</i>

00:24:16.889 --> 00:24:19.432
<i>(Möller) The biggest hit</i>
<i>was a song called</i> Set It Off

00:24:19.558 --> 00:24:22.810
<i>which was when PW Botha</i>
<i>was the president then.</i>

00:24:22.895 --> 00:24:26.731
The real bad guy. When he came on TV,
he used to talk like that.

00:24:28.317 --> 00:24:30.985
<i>And this song said, ''switch it off,</i>
<i>just switch off the TV.''</i>

00:24:39.786 --> 00:24:41.162
<i>(male interviewer)</i>
So what lines do you think

00:24:41.246 --> 00:24:42.830
were the lines they had problem with?

00:24:42.915 --> 00:24:44.415
Ah, gee whiz, it's all of them.

00:24:44.917 --> 00:24:47.627
''Sugar Man, won't you hurry
Cos I'm tired of these scenes

00:24:47.753 --> 00:24:52.089
''For a blue coin, won't you bring back
all those colours to my dreams?''

00:24:52.132 --> 00:24:54.008
The most difficult ones is probably

00:24:54.092 --> 00:24:58.471
''Silver magic ships, you carry
Jumpers, coke, sweet Mary Jane.''

00:24:58.597 --> 00:25:00.181
And what is that?

00:25:00.766 --> 00:25:02.141
Uh...

00:25:02.434 --> 00:25:03.851
I'm gonna leave that to you.

00:25:03.936 --> 00:25:05.353
(both chuckle)

00:25:05.437 --> 00:25:07.855
-But it's drugs?
-It's certainly drugs.

00:25:07.940 --> 00:25:11.859
During the apartheid years,
it was just impossible to play it.

00:25:11.944 --> 00:25:13.861
And what happened if you did play it?

00:25:13.946 --> 00:25:17.114
Well, you couldn't.
I'd like to show you why.

00:25:21.995 --> 00:25:24.872
Right, here we have the album,
the vinyl.

00:25:24.957 --> 00:25:28.459
At the back of the sleeve
you'll see a sticker that says ''Avoid.''

00:25:28.502 --> 00:25:32.296
But when you open the album
and take it out from its sleeve,

00:25:33.048 --> 00:25:36.509
you would see that they have
scratched that particular song

00:25:36.635 --> 00:25:40.304
with a sharp tool to make sure
that it would not go out on air.

00:25:40.847 --> 00:25:45.351
<i>And that's the way that they</i>
<i>banned the music which, in my mind,</i>

00:25:45.477 --> 00:25:50.147
<i>was quite a brutal way of ensuring the</i>
<i>song would never be heard on the air.</i>

00:25:50.649 --> 00:25:54.151
<i>(Steve Harris) Most of those tracks</i>
<i>were on the banned list at SABC</i>

00:25:54.236 --> 00:25:57.572
<i>and they ran</i>
<i>the broadcast industry completely.</i>

00:25:57.656 --> 00:26:00.408
<i>There weren't any independent</i>
<i>radio stations or TV stations.</i>

00:26:00.492 --> 00:26:06.205
Obviously, when that word got out,
it just made the record more desirable.

00:26:07.040 --> 00:26:09.000
You know,
it's like having something banned.

00:26:09.042 --> 00:26:12.587
You're 16, 17 years old
and you've got something that's banned.

00:26:12.671 --> 00:26:14.589
It was absolutely perfect.

00:26:14.881 --> 00:26:17.174
<i>(</i>♫ <i>Can't get Away</i> by Rodriguez)

00:26:34.943 --> 00:26:37.570
♫ <i>Born in the troubled city</i>

00:26:38.572 --> 00:26:41.407
♫ <i>In Rock and Roll, USA</i>

00:26:41.908 --> 00:26:45.286
♫ <i>In the shadow of the tallest building</i>

00:26:46.246 --> 00:26:49.165
♫ <i>I vowed I would break away</i>

00:26:50.292 --> 00:26:53.210
♫ <i>Listened to the Sunday actors</i>

00:26:53.962 --> 00:26:56.464
♫ <i>But all they would ever say</i>

00:26:56.548 --> 00:27:00.134
♫ <i>That you can't get away from it</i>

00:27:00.218 --> 00:27:02.678
♫ <i>No, you can't get away</i>

00:27:03.388 --> 00:27:06.849
<i>(Segerman)</i> Cold Fact <i>was just one</i>
<i>of the albums we had in our collections,</i>

00:27:06.933 --> 00:27:11.228
<i>and for 10, 20 years, it was just</i>
<i>a record we listened to and enjoyed.</i>

00:27:11.897 --> 00:27:15.441
<i>But then a pivotal event happened</i>
<i>that changed everything for me.</i>

00:27:15.525 --> 00:27:16.984
<i>We were down in Camps Bay beach.</i>

00:27:17.069 --> 00:27:20.196
We were sitting around on the beach
and a friend of mine,

00:27:20.280 --> 00:27:22.573
a woman, who was from South Africa,

00:27:22.658 --> 00:27:26.869
but she had got married
and emigrated to Los Angeles,

00:27:26.953 --> 00:27:31.332
she said to me, ''Where can I
buy <i>Cold Fact</i> in South Africa?''

00:27:31.416 --> 00:27:35.252
And I turned round and I pointed
to a store across the road

00:27:35.337 --> 00:27:38.589
that sold CDs and I said,
''You can buy it at that store.''

00:27:38.674 --> 00:27:42.259
She said, ''Really? Because, you know,
you can't buy it anywhere in America.

00:27:42.344 --> 00:27:44.553
''I've asked everywhere in America,
no one's even heard of it.''

00:27:44.638 --> 00:27:47.139
<i>And that was a pivotal moment,</i>
<i>'cause I didn't know that.</i>

00:27:47.224 --> 00:27:48.599
<i>I thought everybody knew Rodriguez,</i>

00:27:48.684 --> 00:27:51.227
<i>especially in America</i>
<i>'cause he was American.</i>

00:27:51.311 --> 00:27:54.438
<i>So my next thought was,</i>
<i>''Ah, Rodriguez, that's interesting.''</i>

00:27:54.523 --> 00:27:56.941
<i>I went back... I came back home</i>
<i>and I took out my Rodriguez records</i>

00:27:57.025 --> 00:27:59.443
<i>and that's when I realised</i>
<i>there was nothing on the record</i>

00:27:59.528 --> 00:28:01.696
<i>to tell us who he was</i>
<i>or where he was from.</i>

00:28:02.072 --> 00:28:03.948
On <i>Cold Fact</i> there are four names.

00:28:04.032 --> 00:28:06.909
On the front cover
it just says ''Rodriguez.''

00:28:06.993 --> 00:28:09.787
But if we take the record out
and examine the sleeve,

00:28:09.913 --> 00:28:12.707
the artist's name is Sixto Rodriguez.

00:28:12.791 --> 00:28:14.291
<i>But if you look at the tracks,</i>

00:28:14.376 --> 00:28:16.001
<i>six of these tracks</i>

00:28:16.086 --> 00:28:18.462
<i>are credited to Jesus Rodriguez,</i>

00:28:18.547 --> 00:28:19.922
<i>and four of these tracks</i>

00:28:20.006 --> 00:28:22.633
<i>are credited to Sixth Prince.</i>

00:28:22.718 --> 00:28:24.385
<i>So who actually wrote these songs</i>

00:28:24.469 --> 00:28:25.720
<i>and who are all these people?</i>

00:28:25.804 --> 00:28:28.973
<i>We didn't have any more information</i>
<i>than a record</i>

00:28:29.057 --> 00:28:32.601
<i>with him sitting on the cover</i>
<i>with a hat and sunglasses on.</i>

00:28:32.686 --> 00:28:35.688
<i>We didn't know how tall he was</i>
<i>'cause he was sitting cross-legged.</i>

00:28:35.772 --> 00:28:37.231
<i>So how do you solve a mystery?</i>

00:28:37.315 --> 00:28:39.316
<i>You use whatever</i>
<i>information's available.</i>

00:28:39.401 --> 00:28:42.695
<i>What did we have?</i>
<i>A record cover with lyrics.</i>

00:28:42.779 --> 00:28:44.447
So we started looking
quite deeply at the lyrics

00:28:44.531 --> 00:28:45.990
and seeing what they said,

00:28:46.074 --> 00:28:48.701
and some of them, very few of them,
had geographical references.

00:28:48.785 --> 00:28:51.412
The one <i>You Can't Get Away</i> starts off,

00:28:51.496 --> 00:28:53.122
''Born in the troubled city

00:28:53.206 --> 00:28:56.000
''In Rock and Roll, USA.''

00:28:56.084 --> 00:28:57.501
Born in which troubled city?

00:28:57.586 --> 00:28:59.670
Seems all the cities were troubled
in the late '60s.

00:28:59.755 --> 00:29:02.047
''In the shadow of the tallest building.''

00:29:02.132 --> 00:29:04.300
The tallest building, as far as we knew,
was in New York.

00:29:04.384 --> 00:29:06.719
And at the bottom of the song
this verse says,

00:29:06.803 --> 00:29:08.429
''In a hotel room in Amsterdam.''

00:29:09.347 --> 00:29:14.351
Then it says, ''Going down a dusty
Georgian side road I wander.'' Georgia?

00:29:14.436 --> 00:29:16.353
So we've had Amsterdam,
we've had Georgia,

00:29:16.438 --> 00:29:17.897
we've had the world's tallest building.

00:29:18.565 --> 00:29:20.274
Not much to go on.

00:29:28.033 --> 00:29:29.450
<i>(Bartholomew-Strydom)</i>
<i>Well, what I heard,</i>

00:29:29.493 --> 00:29:30.910
<i>and the story differs a lot,</i>

00:29:31.036 --> 00:29:34.622
<i>and a lot of people have different</i>
<i>versions of the story, but what I heard,</i>

00:29:34.706 --> 00:29:37.416
<i>he hadn't played a concert</i>
<i>in a very long time.</i>

00:29:37.459 --> 00:29:41.378
And a promoter got him
to play a concert,

00:29:41.463 --> 00:29:44.131
and he was hoping
it was gonna be a great show.

00:29:44.216 --> 00:29:47.343
Of course, the show didn't
work out that way. It started out...

00:29:47.427 --> 00:29:51.430
The sound wasn't good.
The venue wasn't good.

00:29:51.473 --> 00:29:54.141
A lot of the factors
surrounding the show wasn't good.

00:29:54.226 --> 00:29:56.101
And as the show went on and on,

00:29:56.186 --> 00:30:00.773
it started going downhill from there.
People started ridiculing him.

00:30:00.857 --> 00:30:06.153
People started whistling
or making mention of the fact that,

00:30:06.238 --> 00:30:08.614
you know,
the show wasn't going as planned.

00:30:08.698 --> 00:30:12.284
And it got to a point where,
just very quietly, very gently,

00:30:12.369 --> 00:30:13.828
he just sang his last song.

00:30:13.912 --> 00:30:16.580
''But thanks for your time
Then you can thank me for mine

00:30:16.665 --> 00:30:18.624
''And after that's said forget it.''

00:30:18.708 --> 00:30:23.045
And he reached down and pulled up a gun
and pulled the trigger.

00:30:23.630 --> 00:30:26.799
And that was the dramatic,
very dramatic ending,

00:30:26.883 --> 00:30:29.468
to what was actually a non-career.

00:31:00.500 --> 00:31:04.670
<i>(Segerman)</i> In 1996,
the South African record label

00:31:04.754 --> 00:31:08.966
released Rodriguez's second album,
<i>Coming From Reality,</i>

00:31:09.092 --> 00:31:11.886
on CD for the first time
in South Africa.

00:31:11.970 --> 00:31:14.471
And because they thought
I knew a lot about him,

00:31:14.514 --> 00:31:17.224
they asked if I wanted to co-write
the liner notes for the booklet,

00:31:17.309 --> 00:31:18.684
which I did.

00:31:18.768 --> 00:31:23.147
And I'll read some of it to you.
They start off by saying,

00:31:23.231 --> 00:31:26.650
''If ever there is an air of intrigue
and mystery around a pop artist,

00:31:26.735 --> 00:31:29.445
''it is around the artist
known as Rodriguez.

00:31:29.529 --> 00:31:32.656
''There's no air of intrigue and mystery
around him anywhere else in the world

00:31:32.741 --> 00:31:35.868
''because his two albums,
<i>Coming From Reality</i> and <i>Cold Fact,</i>

00:31:35.952 --> 00:31:38.746
''were monumental flops everywhere else.''

00:31:38.830 --> 00:31:40.289
And this is the important part.

00:31:40.999 --> 00:31:44.960
''There were no concrete cold facts
about the artist known as Rodriguez.

00:31:45.045 --> 00:31:47.463
''Any musicologist detectives out there?''

00:31:47.964 --> 00:31:50.758
And that,
that's the line that changed everything.

00:31:51.885 --> 00:31:53.677
<i>(Bartholomew-Strydom)</i>
<i>I started searching for Rodriguez</i>

00:31:53.762 --> 00:31:55.971
<i>when a few of us</i>
<i>were sitting around in the Army</i>

00:31:56.056 --> 00:31:58.432
<i>and somebody said,</i>
<i>''How did Rodriguez die?''</i>

00:31:58.516 --> 00:31:59.892
And just coincidence,

00:31:59.976 --> 00:32:02.394
at the time I was looking
for subject matter to write an article.

00:32:02.479 --> 00:32:05.356
<i>I remember having, like, five points</i>
<i>on a piece of paper.</i>

00:32:05.440 --> 00:32:08.776
<i>And number four, or something,</i>
<i>was ''Find out how Rodriguez died.''</i>

00:32:08.860 --> 00:32:11.570
<i>I thought it would make a good story.</i>

00:32:11.613 --> 00:32:13.697
So that was in the back of my mind
for many years

00:32:13.782 --> 00:32:17.534
and then, many years later,
I came across this, um,

00:32:18.078 --> 00:32:23.415
re-release of <i>Coming From Reality</i>
and inside, the liner notes said,

00:32:23.500 --> 00:32:26.877
''There were no concrete cold facts
about the artist known as Rodriguez.

00:32:26.962 --> 00:32:31.590
''Any musicologist detectives out there?''
Um, was the question,

00:32:31.675 --> 00:32:33.801
and I think that to me,
was like an invitation.

00:32:33.885 --> 00:32:35.970
I thought, ''Well, maybe it's me''.

00:32:38.431 --> 00:32:42.768
<i>The first way I tried to find him</i>
<i>was to just follow the money.</i>

00:32:42.852 --> 00:32:44.103
Normally, you follow the money.

00:32:44.229 --> 00:32:45.604
That's how you get
to the bottom of anything.

00:32:46.272 --> 00:32:48.607
<i>But where do dead men's money go?</i>

00:32:48.692 --> 00:32:51.068
<i>I was astounded that</i>
<i>no one knew anything about him.</i>

00:32:51.194 --> 00:32:55.489
<i>I guess it was reminiscent</i>
<i>of how bad the music industry was.</i>

00:32:55.573 --> 00:32:57.408
<i>They were renowned</i>
<i>for ripping people off.</i>

00:32:57.492 --> 00:33:01.412
And it is one thing,
if they had said to me, ''Oh, yeah,

00:33:01.496 --> 00:33:05.833
''we send the money
to X place or Y,'' or whatever,

00:33:05.917 --> 00:33:08.210
but they just kept on being very vague.

00:33:08.294 --> 00:33:12.047
<i>And, in fact, when I put some pressure</i>
<i>on somebody, I did get an address,</i>

00:33:12.132 --> 00:33:13.632
<i>and I called</i>

00:33:13.717 --> 00:33:16.635
<i>and, I can't remember</i>
<i>if I spoke to someone or left a message,</i>

00:33:16.678 --> 00:33:19.638
<i>but when I called the next day,</i>
<i>the number had been changed.</i>

00:33:19.681 --> 00:33:20.848
<i>And that to me was...</i>

00:33:20.932 --> 00:33:24.351
I mean, that's a gift
for anyone who wants to be a detective,

00:33:24.936 --> 00:33:28.897
is an obstacle,
because an obstacle is an inspiration.

00:33:28.982 --> 00:33:31.608
If you just find things easily,
they're not inspiring,

00:33:31.651 --> 00:33:34.945
and this was a great obstacle
that somebody had changed their number.

00:33:35.030 --> 00:33:39.450
I just smelt a dirty money story
somewhere there.

00:33:39.534 --> 00:33:41.243
<i>(male interviewer)</i>
<i>So, if you compare to other artists,</i>

00:33:41.327 --> 00:33:42.953
<i>how big was it actually?</i>

00:33:43.038 --> 00:33:45.080
<i>(Robbie Mann) Every month it just sold.</i>

00:33:45.165 --> 00:33:48.042
<i>And every party you went to</i>
<i>and every place you went to,</i>

00:33:48.126 --> 00:33:50.544
<i>you'd hear that album at least once.</i>

00:33:50.628 --> 00:33:55.007
I don't think I could even think
of how many albums he's sold here

00:33:55.091 --> 00:33:57.551
'cause it's a long period of time.

00:33:57.927 --> 00:34:00.721
<i>(male interviewer)</i>
What could be probable?

00:34:02.140 --> 00:34:03.724
(sighs)

00:34:03.808 --> 00:34:08.020
I'd have to guess. Maybe half a million
copies over that period of time.

00:34:08.938 --> 00:34:11.774
<i>It's a lot of records,</i>
<i>especially for a small country.</i>

00:34:11.858 --> 00:34:14.318
<i>Gold record, ten times over.</i>

00:34:14.402 --> 00:34:17.154
<i>(male interviewer)</i> Rodriguez never got
to know that he was big in South Africa.

00:34:17.280 --> 00:34:18.697
How could that be?

00:34:18.740 --> 00:34:22.034
Don't know.
I mean, everything would have been...

00:34:22.118 --> 00:34:23.702
I find that strange.

00:34:24.662 --> 00:34:26.038
<i>I have no idea.</i>

00:34:26.122 --> 00:34:28.165
<i>(male interviewer) But you must</i>
<i>have sent royalties somewhere?</i>

00:34:28.291 --> 00:34:30.918
<i>(Mann) Of course we sent royalties.</i>
<i>We sent royalties to A&M Records.</i>

00:34:31.002 --> 00:34:33.295
<i>I remember the label. It was A&M Sussex.</i>

00:34:33.379 --> 00:34:36.298
<i>Whether they had a partnership,</i>
<i>whatever they had, I don't... You know.</i>

00:34:36.925 --> 00:34:41.136
So, my suggestion is, if you
can find out whoever the person was

00:34:41.221 --> 00:34:42.888
who owned Sussex Records,

00:34:43.640 --> 00:34:46.391
then you will find out
what happened to the money.

00:34:46.476 --> 00:34:49.186
<i>(male interviewer)</i>
<i>Because it's weird, isn't it?</i>

00:34:49.312 --> 00:34:52.439
<i>(Mann) It's very strange. Very strange.</i>

00:34:52.524 --> 00:34:54.733
<i>(male interviewer)</i> How popular
was the album? Was he as famous as,

00:34:54.776 --> 00:34:56.944
you know,
the Rolling Stones and the Doors?

00:34:57.070 --> 00:34:58.821
Oh, it was much bigger
than Rolling Stones.

00:34:58.905 --> 00:35:00.364
Absolutely, at the time, yeah.

00:35:00.907 --> 00:35:03.784
<i>(male interviewer) When you released</i>
<i>the record, did you try to contact him?</i>

00:35:03.868 --> 00:35:07.663
<i>(Harris)</i> No, not at all. You know?
Because... because, at the time,

00:35:07.747 --> 00:35:11.750
the legend... the legend was...
here was an artist.

00:35:11.793 --> 00:35:13.710
This was like Jimi Hendrix.

00:35:13.753 --> 00:35:16.463
With Jimi Hendrix catalogues,
you've gotta understand,

00:35:16.548 --> 00:35:21.969
if you just got Jimi Hendrix and you'd
got the licence for this territory,

00:35:22.053 --> 00:35:25.472
you're obviously not gonna go try get
hold of Jimi Hendrix, because he's dead.

00:35:25.557 --> 00:35:28.475
-But who did you pay royalties to?
-To Sussex Music.

00:35:28.560 --> 00:35:29.935
To Clarence?

00:35:30.019 --> 00:35:33.272
Yes. Well, to Sussex Music
which is his company, yeah.

00:35:33.606 --> 00:35:35.566
So, I decided to make a diagram.

00:35:35.608 --> 00:35:38.819
Write down the whole path
and trail that I was trying to work out.

00:35:38.903 --> 00:35:41.572
All the various touch points,
all the record companies,

00:35:41.656 --> 00:35:45.075
all the people that had dealings with
Rodriguez and his album at some point.

00:35:45.160 --> 00:35:47.077
<i>I made this whole document.</i>

00:35:47.162 --> 00:35:49.746
<i>So I found out there were three</i>
<i>record companies in South Africa</i>

00:35:49.789 --> 00:35:52.291
<i>that had released Rodriguez's records.</i>

00:35:52.417 --> 00:35:56.044
<i>Finally discovering that</i>
<i>led to a record company in America.</i>

00:35:56.129 --> 00:35:57.921
<i>It was a company that</i>
<i>had been signing Rodriguez</i>

00:35:58.006 --> 00:36:00.841
<i>and creating his first album</i>
<i>called Sussex.</i>

00:36:01.676 --> 00:36:03.719
<i>I then did my research on Sussex.</i>

00:36:03.803 --> 00:36:05.971
<i>That led me to discovering</i>

00:36:06.055 --> 00:36:10.475
<i>who the owner of Sussex Records was:</i>
<i>Clarence Avant.</i>

00:36:10.560 --> 00:36:12.811
<i>Clarence Avant,</i>
<i>he'd been the head of Motown,</i>

00:36:12.854 --> 00:36:16.481
<i>one of the most prestigious jobs</i>
<i>to have in the record company industry.</i>

00:36:16.566 --> 00:36:20.277
So I did my research. I tried everything
to get a hold of Clarence Avant,

00:36:20.403 --> 00:36:23.822
but I just got to a lot of closed doors.
I could not get a hold of him.

00:36:36.044 --> 00:36:39.296
<i>(male interviewer)</i> I don't know
if you've ever seen this picture.

00:36:39.422 --> 00:36:42.049
(chuckles) That's him.

00:36:44.260 --> 00:36:46.053
That's Rodriguez.

00:36:47.597 --> 00:36:49.890
I don't know when this was made.
I have absolutely no idea.

00:36:49.974 --> 00:36:52.893
-That's 1970, I think.
-Yeah.

00:36:55.271 --> 00:36:57.189
This is my man.

00:37:01.361 --> 00:37:03.862
Man, don't get me emotional again. Shit.

00:37:03.905 --> 00:37:05.322
You made me emotional once.

00:37:05.448 --> 00:37:08.909
I ain't getting emotional no more
sitting here talking to you, man.

00:37:10.370 --> 00:37:14.790
<i>If I had to name ten artists</i>
<i>that I have ever been involved with,</i>

00:37:14.874 --> 00:37:17.626
<i>Rodriguez would be in the top five,</i>
<i>simple as that.</i>

00:37:17.710 --> 00:37:19.753
<i>There's nothing...</i>
<i>You never heard anything like him.</i>

00:37:19.837 --> 00:37:23.215
<i>People would say, ''Well, Bob Dylan.''</i>
<i>I said, ''No, no''.</i>

00:37:23.299 --> 00:37:27.636
<i>Bob Dylan was mild to this guy.</i>
<i>Did it make any money?</i>

00:37:27.720 --> 00:37:29.972
We judge singing here in America...

00:37:30.014 --> 00:37:33.517
If you say,
''Is it... Was it the top hundred?

00:37:33.601 --> 00:37:37.771
''Was it... was it number...
Did it get on the charts as number 12?

00:37:37.855 --> 00:37:41.275
''Was there a lot of radio play?''
The answer's, ''No, man.''

00:37:42.652 --> 00:37:44.861
Nobody didn't... Rodriguez?

00:37:46.114 --> 00:37:48.699
You know, that name didn't register.

00:37:49.492 --> 00:37:52.369
Although he looked like he was
a white guy but, even still, Rodriguez,

00:37:52.495 --> 00:37:55.372
everybody knew Rodriguez,
that's a Spanish name.

00:37:55.498 --> 00:37:58.292
A Latin name.
Latin music was not happening then.

00:37:58.376 --> 00:38:00.877
<i>(male interviewer)</i> How many records
do you think he sold in America?

00:38:00.962 --> 00:38:03.171
In America? Six.

00:38:03.214 --> 00:38:05.299
Maybe my wife bought it,
maybe my daughter bought...

00:38:05.383 --> 00:38:09.011
She couldn't buy it, but maybe
Neil Bogart, maybe Dennis and Mike.

00:38:09.053 --> 00:38:13.390
Hey, look, man, you know,
it didn't sell here.

00:38:14.058 --> 00:38:16.893
<i>There was some excitement about him.</i>

00:38:16.978 --> 00:38:21.356
<i>Couple of agents heard him</i>
<i>and wanted to bring him to California</i>

00:38:21.399 --> 00:38:24.568
<i>and, you know, when he came</i>
<i>to California he was nervous,</i>

00:38:24.694 --> 00:38:26.737
<i>and he turned his back to the audience</i>

00:38:26.863 --> 00:38:29.031
<i>and everybody said,</i>
<i>''Well, what the hell is this?''</i>

00:38:29.073 --> 00:38:30.574
<i>(male interviewer)</i>
<i>But the thing is that the guy sold</i>

00:38:30.658 --> 00:38:33.410
<i>hundreds of thousands of records</i>
<i>in another country.</i>

00:38:33.536 --> 00:38:35.746
<i>(Avant) I'm going to South Africa to try</i>
<i>to chase somebody who's selling records?</i>

00:38:35.830 --> 00:38:37.205
<i>Shit, no, man.</i>

00:38:37.248 --> 00:38:39.916
<i>(male interviewer) But did you know</i>
<i>that he was big in South Africa?</i>

00:38:39.917 --> 00:38:44.921
Rodriguez, young man, never happened
insofar as I'm concerned.

00:38:45.048 --> 00:38:46.423
Period.

00:38:46.591 --> 00:38:50.844
But if I'm really gonna try to track
down the money, how should I do it?

00:38:50.928 --> 00:38:53.430
Well, is that important, the money?
Or is Rod...

00:38:53.556 --> 00:38:58.935
Which is important? Rodriguez's story
or you worrying about the money?

00:38:59.020 --> 00:39:00.604
How many people in South Africa?

00:39:00.730 --> 00:39:03.440
40 million? 40 thousand?
40 million people? How many people?

00:39:03.566 --> 00:39:05.025
40 million people live in South Africa.

00:39:05.109 --> 00:39:08.737
Well, so they've been freed
for how long? Three hours?

00:39:08.946 --> 00:39:10.238
So what the fuck's
that supposed to mean?

00:39:10.281 --> 00:39:12.949
You told me at lunch,
they scratch records

00:39:13.076 --> 00:39:14.701
because they wouldn't let the lyrics...

00:39:14.786 --> 00:39:18.288
So the underground movement,
how big was it? How big was it?

00:39:18.414 --> 00:39:20.957
<i>(male interviewer)</i> He sold
half a million records in South Africa.

00:39:21.084 --> 00:39:22.876
So he sold half a million records.
So what?

00:39:22.960 --> 00:39:24.711
I don't know who he sold them to.

00:39:24.796 --> 00:39:27.631
How many distributors did he have?
I have no idea.

00:39:27.715 --> 00:39:29.216
There are only...
There are three record labels.

00:39:29.300 --> 00:39:31.134
-I spoke to all the record label...
-Well, great.

00:39:31.260 --> 00:39:35.972
...bosses in South Africa who
has released his records. It was...

00:39:36.140 --> 00:39:38.725
Go back to 'em and tell 'em
to send me an account.

00:39:38.810 --> 00:39:41.228
You think it's something
I'm gonna worry about, a 1970 contract?

00:39:41.312 --> 00:39:43.980
If you do,
you're outta your goddamn mind.

00:39:44.107 --> 00:39:47.818
Buddha Records out of business.
I'm out of business.

00:39:48.945 --> 00:39:53.156
So you think they give a shit
about that? I know I wouldn't.

00:39:55.785 --> 00:39:57.160
<i>(Segerman)</i>
<i>I've been looking for information</i>

00:39:57.286 --> 00:39:58.912
<i>about Rodriguez for a long time.</i>

00:39:59.831 --> 00:40:03.083
<i>I've even set up a web page</i>
<i>called The Great Rodriguez Hunt</i>

00:40:03.167 --> 00:40:05.168
<i>in the hope that</i>
<i>someone out there in cyberspace</i>

00:40:05.294 --> 00:40:09.965
<i>would post a message on the forum giving</i>
<i>us any information about Rodriguez.</i>

00:40:10.466 --> 00:40:11.967
<i>But there was nothing.</i>

00:40:12.760 --> 00:40:14.678
<i>At that stage I met Craig,</i>

00:40:14.762 --> 00:40:18.014
<i>who was the musicologist detective</i>
<i>who had read my liner notes</i>

00:40:18.141 --> 00:40:20.267
<i>and who was also</i>
<i>searching for Rodriguez.</i>

00:40:20.351 --> 00:40:23.687
<i>And he flew down to Cape Town</i>
<i>and we met in a coffee shop.</i>

00:40:23.771 --> 00:40:26.523
<i>And we exchanged</i>
<i>all the information we had.</i>

00:40:26.691 --> 00:40:28.984
<i>But unfortunately we had very little.</i>

00:40:29.026 --> 00:40:33.280
<i>And at that stage I remember we felt</i>
<i>it was probably best if we just stopped.</i>

00:40:33.364 --> 00:40:34.865
<i>(Bartholomew-Strydom)</i>
<i>So basically I was lost.</i>

00:40:34.991 --> 00:40:36.658
<i>I'd come to a dead end.</i>
<i>I couldn't find him.</i>

00:40:36.701 --> 00:40:38.285
<i>I didn't know where to look any more.</i>

00:40:38.369 --> 00:40:40.704
<i>I'd even visited the places</i>
<i>that he sang about.</i>

00:40:40.830 --> 00:40:42.831
<i>I'd been to London. Nothing.</i>

00:40:42.874 --> 00:40:47.043
<i>I'd been to Amsterdam.</i>
<i>He sings about Amsterdam. Nothing.</i>

00:40:47.128 --> 00:40:49.963
<i>And one day I'd basically given up.</i>
<i>I thought, ''Well, this is it.''</i>

00:40:50.047 --> 00:40:52.883
And one day, just by accident,
I was listening to the album in the car

00:40:53.009 --> 00:40:55.051
and I heard the song <i>Inner City Blues</i>.

00:40:55.136 --> 00:40:57.304
<i>Great song. And the line came up.</i>

00:40:57.388 --> 00:41:01.141
<i>''I met a girl in Dearborn,</i>
<i>early six o'clock this morn.</i>

00:41:01.225 --> 00:41:02.726
<i>''A cold fact.''</i>

00:41:02.810 --> 00:41:05.812
<i>Then I thought, ''Hang on a minute.''</i>
<i>I'd never checked out Dearborn.</i>

00:41:05.897 --> 00:41:07.814
<i>I didn't even know if it was a city</i>
<i>but then I thought,</i>

00:41:07.899 --> 00:41:09.733
<i>''Actually that sounds</i>
<i>like a town or a city.''</i>

00:41:09.817 --> 00:41:13.528
And I thought, ''Hang on,
let me check it out in an atlas.''

00:41:13.571 --> 00:41:18.700
So I went through to my old atlas
and pulled it out.

00:41:18.743 --> 00:41:22.078
I thought, ''Let me see
what I could find here.

00:41:22.079 --> 00:41:24.581
''Let me see if I could find Dearborn.''

00:41:24.749 --> 00:41:26.416
Um... Dear...

00:41:27.251 --> 00:41:31.379
Then I found it.
Dearborn, Wayne, Michigan. F7.

00:41:34.926 --> 00:41:37.594
F...7.

00:41:37.720 --> 00:41:42.766
Dearborn. Part of Detroit.
That was a huge breakthrough in my mind.

00:41:42.850 --> 00:41:47.521
Detroit, home of Motown,
Marvin Gaye, Stevie Wonder,

00:41:48.189 --> 00:41:51.107
and, eventually, Mike Theodore,
the producer of the album.

00:41:55.947 --> 00:42:00.116
<i>(Theodore) I was sitting in my condo,</i>
<i>just having a cup of coffee.</i>

00:42:00.117 --> 00:42:04.120
<i>I was looking out the window</i>
